 * ║    for critical events: debt/credit/slip success).             ║
 * ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
 *
 * What it does:
 *   - Daily cron `dinoco_audit_retention_cron` (registered via
 *     dinoco_register_cron — heartbeat + Health Monitor visibility)
 *   - Helper API: dinoco_audit_retention_run( $dry_run = false )
 *   - Archive: CSV (gzip) → wp-content/uploads/audit-archive/YYYY-MM/
 *   - Stats persisted to wp_options `_dinoco_audit_retention_last_run`
 *     (JSON: { ran_at, archived, deleted, kept, errors, elapsed_ms })
 *   - Self-audit row: writes event_type=retention_run to audit_log
 *     itself (so retention runs are forensic-visible)
 *
 * Config keys (registered via dinoco_register_config — Config Layer):
 *   audit.retention_days        int  default 90   — events older = archive candidate
 *   audit.archive_days          int  default 180  — events older = hard-delete candidate
 *   audit.critical_retention_days int default 365 — keep critical 1y minimum
 *   audit.batch_size            int  default 5000 — rows per archive/delete batch
 *
 * Critical event types (long-retention whitelist):
 *   debt_subtract, debt_add, credit_subtract, credit_add,
 *   slip_apply, slip_review_decision, manual_admin_paid,
 *   stock_add, stock_subtract, stock_transfer, fsm_transition,
 *   po_create, po_complete, config_change, retention_run
 *
 * Backward compat:
 *   - Disabling this snippet → cron stops; existing rows untouched
 *   - Schema unchanged (no ALTER) — pure read/archive/delete
 *   - dry_run mode = inspect counts only, NO mutation
 *
 * Security:
 *   - Manual run requires manage_options + nonce
 *   - Archive folder protected via .htaccess deny + index.php placeholder
 *   - Path traversal defense: archive subdir generated server-side only
 */

